edu.jhu.cs.damsl.engine.storage
Class Tuple

java.lang.Object
  DuplicatedChannelBuffer
      edu.jhu.cs.damsl.engine.storage.Tuple

public class Tuple
extends DuplicatedChannelBuffer

Tuples, the basic unit of dataflow, implemented on top of Netty buffers. Tuples can either be singletons or multi-tuples. TODO: uniform implementation of singletons and multi-tuples. Singletons should not use a heap-allocated header. TODO: internal class for tuple headers.

Version:
0.1
Author:
Yanif Ahmad

emptyTuple

public static Tuple emptyTuple(ChannelBuffer alloc,
                               int requestedSize,
                               int tupleSize)
Creates a multi-tuple backed by the given buffer. We explicitly set the writerIndex to match the buffer we're allocating from, and advance the given buffer's writerIndex to ensure it does not overwrite any operations on this tuple. Notes: tupleSize here should include the header size. The result contains a valid count only if the tupleSize is positive. Also, requestedSize should be integer multiples of tupleSize if the latter is positive.

emptyTuple

public static Tuple emptyTuple(int requestedSize,
                               boolean varLength)
Creates a single heap-allocated tuple of the requested size, which should NOT include the header. Notes: the result is a single tuple with fixed length if indicated.

schemaTuple

public static Tuple schemaTuple(Schema schema,
                                java.util.List<java.lang.Object> fields)
Creates a single heap-allocated tuple filled from the given fields. Returns null if the schema does not return a valid tuple size for the instance.

skipTuple

public static boolean skipTuple(ChannelBuffer source,
                                int tupleSize,
                                int limitIndex)
Skips over the next tuple in the source buffer. Performs an unchecked skip of the specified number of bytes. Tuple size here should include the header size.

Parameters:
source - the buffer containing a tuple to skip
tupleSize - the size of the tuple
Returns:
whether we successfully skipped a tuple

skipTuple
